# butter_setref_clean_2026-05-29.meta
# Provenance for butter_setref_clean_2026-05-29.tsv (task #148)

## What this measures
butteraugli-gpu `Butteraugli::set_reference` per-reference cost on a
WARM instance (CUDA context + all kernels JIT'd + cubecl memory pool
populated via a throwaway full-mode `compute` before timing). Isolates
the reference-side precompute (sRGB upload + opsin transform + frequency
separation + reference-only mask pipeline). Each timed `set_reference`
is immediately followed by `block_on(client.sync())` INSIDE the timed
region (set_reference queues GPU work and does NOT read back, so an
un-synced timer would measure submission, not execution — see project
CLAUDE.md "Diagnosing Slow GPU Code").

phases:
  setref1            = FIRST set_reference on the warm instance
  setref2/3/4        = subsequent DISTINCT-pixel references (the "reuse
                       path" #144 flagged: cached-ref planes reused, only
                       per-ref precompute re-runs)
  warm_call          = compute_with_reference per-score (self-syncs via
                       host readback) — the per-comparison cost, separate
                       from the set_reference precompute
Each rep within a phase uses a FRESH-pixel reference (LCG seed varies),
so no two consecutive set_reference calls feed identical bytes (no
identical-input GPU shortcut). ref/dist images pre-generated outside the
timed region.

## Driver
crates/butteraugli-gpu/examples/setref_timing.rs (new, task #148)
Uses the typed `Butteraugli<R>` API directly (NOT the zenmetrics-api
umbrella `Metric`), so the timing is pure butteraugli-gpu with no
umbrella dispatch layer in scope.

Build:
  cargo build --release -p butteraugli-gpu \
    --no-default-features --features cuda --example setref_timing
Run (per size):
  SETREF_W=<w> SETREF_H=<h> SETREF_REPS=8 SETREF_NEWREF_PHASES=3 \
    LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/cuda/lib64:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH \
    ./target/release/examples/setref_timing
(1024 row used REPS=10, a confirmation re-run; medians reproduced the
REPS=8 run within noise.)

