## Quiet-window evidence (the whole point of this re-measure)
Task #144's numbers were contaminated by a concurrent zensim eval on the
GPU. Before EVERY timing run, verified:
  - nvidia-smi --query-compute-apps : EMPTY (0 GPU compute processes) at
    each gate check (00:39, 00:41, 00:43, 00:45, 00:47 UTC).
  - nvidia-smi GPU util: 1% (idle desktop), memory ~3.0-3.4 GiB (WSL2/
    Windows desktop compositor only; no metric process resident).
  - ps: no local cargo/sweep/score/inprocess/setref/vram_leak/cubecl
    process besides this driver. (One sibling agent was running
    `cargo build` over SSH on a REMOTE arm-zen box — no local GPU/CPU.)
  - Fresh sibling .workongoing markers checked: readme-overhaul (docs),
    jobsys-deploy (R2/dashboard), zensim session-persist (parquet
    inventory), upstream-weezl-prs (CPU bench, explicitly "going silent
    to avoid gate trips") — none are GPU consumers; GPU stayed at 0
    compute apps throughout.
Robustness: 8-10 samples per cell, MEDIAN + MIN reported. Two isolated
single-sample transient spikes (~47-49 ms) appeared in 1024 setref2/3
across runs — a periodic WSL2/desktop transient, NOT sustained
contention. Median and min are unaffected (the multi-sample design is
exactly what catches what #144's n=1 sampling missed).

## Result vs task #144 (gpu_inprocess_warmth_2026-05-29.tsv, Q3 butter)
#144 measured each set_reference EXACTLY ONCE (n=1) via the umbrella
`inprocess_warmth.rs` Q3 driver:
  #144 512²  : setref1 = 34.2792 ms   setref2 = 0.7595 ms
  #144 16 MP : setref1 = 3990.4124 ms setref2 = 21.6446 ms

Clean re-measure (this run, n=8-10, median):
                setref1    setref2    setref3    setref4
  512²  (0.26 MP)  0.84 ms    0.83 ms    0.78 ms    0.78 ms
  1024² (1.05 MP)  1.58 ms    1.57 ms    1.50 ms    1.49 ms
  2048² (4.19 MP)  6.23 ms    5.95 ms    5.89 ms    5.74 ms
  4096² (16.78 MP) 22.16 ms   22.48 ms   22.54 ms   22.56 ms

VERDICT — #144's setref1 numbers are CORRECTED; setref2 is CONFIRMED:
  * #144's SUBSEQUENT-new-ref number is CONFIRMED: 0.76 ms @ 512² ≈ this
    run's 0.78-0.83 ms; 21.6 ms @ 16 MP ≈ this run's 22.5 ms. The "reuse
    path is cheap" finding holds.
  * #144's FIRST-ref number is a CONTAMINATION ARTIFACT, not a real
    per-ref cost. On a properly warmed instance there is NO first-ref
    penalty: setref1 ≈ setref2 ≈ setref3 ≈ setref4 at every size. #144's
    34 ms @ 512² and 3990 ms @ 16 MP (180× the real value) were the
    concurrent zensim eval stealing the GPU during that single timed
    call — #144 had no repeated sampling to catch it (its setref1=3990 ms
    at 16 MP is physically implausible: 88× a full warm `compute`, which
    does strictly MORE work, at ~34 ms).
  * THIS clean run is AUTHORITATIVE. butter set_reference is ~constant
    per ref (no "first ref" exception); the genuine per-ref precompute
    is ~0.8 ms @ 512², ~1.5 ms @ 1 MP, ~5.9 ms @ 4 MP, ~22 ms @ 16 MP.
    Scaling is roughly linear in pixels above 1 MP with a sub-ms fixed
    overhead floor.
